{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18625"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18625"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76495"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10242"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26363"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76495"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe forearm can rotate around its long axis through the actions of specific muscles. This movement occurs primarily at the proximal and distal radioulnar joints.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the position of the radius relative to the ulna during supination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crosses over posterior surface of ulna","Parallel to ulna with palm facing upward","Spirals underneath ulna","Crosses over anterior surface of ulna","Rotates medially around ulna"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring supination, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eparallel to ulna with palm facing upward\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the anatomical relationship between the radius and ulna. The radius and ulna lie side by side in the anatomical position, which corresponds to full supination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrosses over anterior surface of ulna\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes pronation, not supination\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotates medially around ulna\u003C/strong\u003E - The radius rotates laterally during pronation, not medially\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrosses over posterior surface of ulna\u003C/strong\u003E - The radius crosses anteriorly, not posteriorly, during pronation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpirals underneath ulna\u003C/strong\u003E - The radius remains lateral to the ulna and does not pass underneath it\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these movements is essential for appreciating how the forearm achieves rotation and how injuries may affect this function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Supination rotates the forearm so the palm faces upward or anteriorly.","Pronation rotates the forearm so the palm faces downward or posteriorly.","The radius crosses over the ulna during pronation while remaining parallel during supination."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18625"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61992","link